<section class="section"><div class="container" style="max-width:820px">
  {[
    {title:'Origins of Old English',body:'Old English descended from the Germanic dialects brought to Britain by the Angles, Saxons, and Jutes — tribes from modern-day northern Germany and Denmark — who began settling in Britain in the 5th century AD. This West Germanic language gradually replaced the Celtic languages spoken by the native Britons in most of England.',points:['Angle dialect (Anglian) became dominant in the north','Saxon dialect shaped the south and west','Jutish influenced Kent and the Isle of Wight']},
    {title:'How Different Is Old English From Modern English?',body:'Old English is dramatically different from modern English. The vocabulary is predominantly Germanic — words like "mann" (man), "wif" (woman), "cild" (child), and "hus" (house) are recognisable, but most Old English vocabulary is unrecognisable to modern readers. The grammar is highly inflected, meaning word endings change to indicate grammatical function — similar to modern German or Latin.',points:['Four grammatical cases: nominative, accusative, dative, genitive','Three grammatical genders: masculine, feminine, neuter','Verb conjugations differ significantly by person and tense']},
    {title:'The Language of Beowulf',body:'The most famous work in Old English is Beowulf — an epic poem of approximately 3,200 lines describing the heroic deeds of the warrior Beowulf. Written down around 1000 AD (though likely composed earlier), it gives us our clearest window into the literary language of the Anglo-Saxons. The poem uses kennings — compound poetic phrases — such as "hwæl-weg" (whale-road, meaning the sea) and "bān-hūs" (bone-house, meaning the body).'},
    {title:'The Norman Conquest and the Death of Old English',body:'In 1066, William the Conqueror\'s Norman invasion transformed England. French became the language of the ruling class, Latin the language of the Church, and Old English was demoted to the speech of the peasantry. Over the next century, it underwent radical change — losing most of its inflectional endings and absorbing thousands of French and Latin words — to become Middle English.'},
    {title:'Old English\'s Legacy in Modern English',body:'Despite its apparent distance, Old English forms the core of modern English. The most common words in English — "the", "be", "to", "and", "a", "in", "is", "it", "of", "that" — are all Old English in origin. Function words, basic nouns (water, earth, fire, air), and many verbs (go, come, see, hear, speak) descend directly from Old English.',points:['Over 4,000 Old English words survived into modern English','Weekday names are all Old English (Monday = Mōnandæg)','Most English place names in England have Old English roots']},
    {title:'Using Old English Today',body:'Old English is studied in university linguistics and literature departments worldwide. It appears in fantasy fiction, video games, and film as a marker of authenticity. Translator Old English offers four historical styles — from the accessible Early Modern style to the deeply archaic Ancient style — making Old English accessible to writers, game developers, and curious learners.'},
